  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, an H-1B visa can be extended beyond the standard 6-year limit if you have an approved I-140 petition with your previous employer and a few specific conditions are met.\n\nUnder the American Competitiveness in the Twenty-First Century Act (AC21), an H-1B visa holder can apply for extensions past the 6-year limit in the following scenarios:\n\n1. **Approved I-140**: If you have an approved I-140 petition from your previous employer and your priority date is current, you are eligible to extend your H-1B status in increments of up to 3 years.\n\n2. **Pending I-140**: If your I-140 petition is still pending for more than 365 days, you may also be eligible for extensions beyond the 6-year limit.\n\n3. **Changing Employers**: If you change employers, the new employer must file a new H-1B petition for you, but the extension eligibility based on the approved I-140 remains valid as long as the petition is still active.\n\n4. **No Job Offer Withdrawal**: If your previous employer withdraws the I-140 after 180 days, you might lose the ability to extend beyond the 6 years, unless you have a new employer who can file a new I-140.\n\nIt's important to work with an immigration attorney to ensure that all requirements are met and that the process goes smoothly when changing employers or extending your H-1B status.",
